\title{Orthogonal basis}
\author{alex-nelson}
\import{notation}
\date{2025-12-08}
\taxon{definition}

\p{Let #{V} be a finite-dimensional real vector space with a well-defined notion of a dot product, let #{B} be a basis of #{V}. We call #{B} an \define{Orthogonal Basis} of #{V} if for all #{f_{i},f_{j}\in B} we have #{f_{i}\cdot f_{j}=0} when #{i\neq j}.}

\p{Note: we do not require #{B} to be an ordered basis for us to discuss an orthogonal basis. If we want to stress that #{B} is ordered and orthogonal, then we will speak of it as an "orthogonal ordered basis" of #{V}.}